const title = "Champion Commercial Dishwasher Repair | Southern California";
const description = "Champion MD-1000, D-HB, UH-100B, 44-Series conveyor, DH-2000, Prodigy HMI repair across Southern California. Ali Group family specialists. (424) 325-0520.";
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/champion-dishwasher-repair/";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is Champion part of Ali Group?",
    a: "Yes, and Champion was Ali Group's very first US acquisition, back in 1980. Luciano Berti bought Champion from AMSCO (American Sterilizer Company) that year, which is how Ali Group entered the American commercial foodservice market. Since 1980, Ali Group has grown into one of the two dominant global foodservice-equipment consolidators (alongside ITW), with a US headquarters at 3765 Champion Blvd in Winston-Salem, NC that shares the Champion plant. Post-2022 Welbilt acquisition, Ali Group's US family also includes Delfield, Manitowoc, Kolpak, Master-Bilt, Nor-Lake, Lincoln, Garland, Pitco, and Frymaster, which is why Champion service can coordinate parts and dispatch across multiple pieces of kitchen equipment in one call for LA operators running an Ali-heavy kitchen build-out."
  },
  {
    q: "What's Prodigy HMI and how do I read its error codes?",
    a: "Prodigy HMI is Champion's touchscreen control system on newer door and conveyor machines. HMI stands for Human-Machine Interface, it replaces the mechanical timer-dial controls of older Champion units with a programmable touchscreen that logs errors, runs proactive-maintenance diagnostics, and tracks cycle counts for service scheduling. Error codes come up on the main display; tapping the error icon brings up a log with the last 50+ events. Common Prodigy HMI codes: WASH TANK TEMP (wash heater or thermostat), RINSE TEMP (booster element or booster thermostat), DOOR OPEN (switch or latch), LOW WATER (fill valve or level sensor), CHEMICAL DISPENSER (detergent or rinse-aid proportioning issue). The log tells us a lot before we even open the front panel."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you service my Champion at our hospital or medical cafeteria?",
    a: "Yes, this is one of Champion's historical strongholds. AMSCO (American Sterilizer Company) was Champion's parent from 1967 to 1980, and during that window Champion built heavy-duty utensil sanitizers for hospital foodservice. The healthcare DNA carries forward: Champion door machines at Cedars-Sinai, UCLA Medical Center, Kaiser Permanente cafeterias, Keck Medical at USC, and Children's Hospital Los Angeles are common. Healthcare service requires documented maintenance records for Joint Commission inspection compliance; we provide service documentation appropriate for healthcare facility records alongside the standard work order."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between Champion MD-1000HT and MD-1000LT?",
    a: "HT is high-temperature sanitizing, the final rinse runs at 180°F, hot enough to sanitize without chemical sanitizer addition. LT is low-temperature chemical sanitizing, rinse at lower temp but with chlorine or quaternary chemical sanitizer dosed into the final rinse to achieve equivalent sanitation. Why choose one over the other? HT machines run higher energy consumption (the 180°F booster is expensive to run at LA gas or electric rates) but simpler chemistry, just detergent and rinse aid. LT machines use less energy but require ongoing sanitizer chemical costs and more careful chemistry balance. For an LA operation with high wash volume and stable water chemistry, HT is usually the lower-total-cost choice; for smaller operations or where chemical sanitizing integrates with other kitchen protocols, LT fits better."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service Bi-Line integrated conveyor systems?",
    a: "Yes, Bi-Line is Champion's sister brand for integrated dishroom conveyor systems, not an independent company. Same Winston-Salem parts channel, same Ali Group service network. Bi-Line systems integrate a pre-wash conveyor, the main rack conveyor or flight-type dishwasher, and a clean-end conveyor into a single continuous dishroom workflow. Common in LA hotel banquet prep, convention-center kitchens, and large institutional foodservice operations. Service overlap with Champion is extensive: drive motors, conveyor chains, dish rack transfer tables, chemical dispensers. Our techs service both on the same account."
  },
  {
    q: "Can one service provider cover our Champion + Moyer Diebel + Kolpak + Beverage-Air equipment?",
    a: "Yes, that's the practical advantage of the Ali Group family approach. Champion + Moyer Diebel (Champion's Canadian sister brand) + Kolpak walk-ins + Master-Bilt walk-ins + Nor-Lake walk-ins + Beverage-Air refrigeration + Delfield refrigeration + Manitowoc ice machines + Scotsman ice machines are all Ali Group brands sharing parts infrastructure. For an LA operator running an Ali-heavy kitchen build-out, common in new hotel and restaurant openings where the equipment package comes from a single dealer, one service call can address multiple Ali brand failures in sequence rather than coordinating three or four separate service companies."
  },
  {
    q: "What does Champion dishwasher repair cost in LA?",
    a: "$120 flat commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. Typical Champion service ranges: door gasket $160–$280, fill solenoid $200–$340, thermostat $180–$300, door switch $150–$240, rinse booster element $280–$460, wash pump seal kit $320–$500, drain pump $280–$440, detergent dispenser $220–$360, Prodigy HMI board $650–$1,100, wash pump rebuild $450–$720, 44-Series conveyor drive $550–$900, control board (non-HMI) $600–$1,000. Most Champion door-machine calls land $350–$700 parts-and-labor; 44-Series and 66-Series rack conveyor jobs run $550–$1,100."
  }
];

